==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Smug
<hw>Smug</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Of. Scand. or Low German
origin; cf. LG. <ets>smuck</ets>, G. <ets>schmuck</ets>, Dan.
<ets>smuk</ets>, OSw. <ets>smuck</ets>, <ets>sm⟦oum⟧ck</ets>, and E.
<ets>smock</ets>, <ets>smuggle</ets>; cf. G. <ets>schmuck</ets>
ornament. See <er>Smock</er>.]</ety> <def>Studiously neat or nice,
especially in dress; spruce; affectedly precise; smooth and
prim.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They be so <qex>smug</qex> and smooth.</q> <rj><qau>Robynson
(More's Utopia).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>smug</qex> and scanty draperies of his style.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A young, <qex>smug</qex>, handsome holiness has no fellow.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Smug
<hw>Smug</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Smugged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Smugging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make smug, or spruce.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus said, he <qex>smugged</qex> his beard, and stroked up
fair.</q> <rj><qau>Dryton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smuggle</ent>⟦br⟧
